pros:
low working pressure;
medium perks,;
Talent intro program in Shanghai to support employee to get permanent residence
friendly working environment for engineers.

The salaries are above average; 
They give 25 vacation days; 
There's a flexibility in the hours (depending on the job); 
There's a performance bonus; 
If the team leader is good, there can be a very nice environment and people can develop a lot.

cons:
Boss - Wether your experience will be good or bad depends almost entirely on your luck with the team leader. I've had 3 team leaders in the same team over the course of 5 years. With the first two, I had such a good experience, I absolutely loved going to work everyday, although the workload was really high. I was given responsibility and was trusted to coordinate whenever needed. When the last team leader came, everything changed. He was "leading by terror" and using the "divide and conquer" on his own team, to split us so we'd be easier to lead. Told me my biggest flaw is empathy. I started despising it there. He was getting along very well with management, so nobody was brave enough to say anything; 
Work from home - we had a maximum of 2 days per week when I was employed, then at some point they simply removed woeking from home regularly, only leaving it for urgent situations. Working from home was one of the top reasons I came to work here; 
Furloughs - Another negative thing here is that if the company results are not where they want, they will make people go on furloughs (if the country laws you work in allows that, of course - but they will still push for it).

